#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The following submission is an indication of discussions; it does not necessarily reflect the individual views of each member of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Anti-Corruption, nor those organisations or individuals in attendance. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Making the EITI work in a UK context</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative (EITI) was originally announced by a British Prime Minister and its principals were agreed at an inaugural conference in London.  We therefore welcome the Prime Minister’s commitment to joining the EITI in May this year and hope an application for candidacy will be forthcoming.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We strongly urge the Government to implement the EITI Standard in a way that truly benefits our domestic extractive industries.  While the sentiment of OECD countries who comply with EITI principals out of solidarity with poorer nations is to be commended, we recommend an approach based on robust consideration of what the principals mean in our specific regulatory framework.  The Government should adapt the implementing mechanisms to fit our particular requirements. We note the example of Australia which is currently undertaking a pilot of EITI to determine how it might meets the precise needs of their mining sector</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Thought should be given to how reporting commitments can improve governance of North Sea oil and inform the current debate around fracking.  EITI reporting could for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">instance be used to determine the 1% community dividend committed by fracking companies</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In demonstrating the importance of national-level ownership and adaption, the UK will do more to advance the EITI principles than it would by simply adhering to its basic requirements.  This could lead to innovative new ways to increase transparency which improve implementation elsewhere. Better global uptake will in turn benefit British investors and companies by increasing stability and good governance in resource rich nations.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Impact of the UK implementing EITI</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Implementation of both the EITI and the EU Accounting and Transparency Directives could bring significant benefits to our domestic extractive industries and the UK has the potential to be a global leader on transparent, open government.  As David Cameron commented before June’s G8 Summit ‘this is the critical moment to get our own houses in order.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’ </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe, however, that the impact will largely depend on whether a number of optional elements are implemented. Based on the experience of now compliant EITI countries, it is clear that publishing the figures paid by governments and companies is only the first step towards meaningfully improving transparency. To act as an effective check-and-balance the information must be accessible and contextualised.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We therefore urge the Government to present data in a format understandable by ordinary citizens which is sufficiently contextualised, including the legal, environmental and social background and to publicly disclose any contracts and licenses that provide the terms attached to the exploitation of oil, gas and minerals, as recommended in the EITI Standard, Article 3.12a</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  As the UK implements the EITI principles, particular consideration should be given to ensuring its reports are actively promoted and contribute to the public debate, a further recommendation in the EITI Standard</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Limiting the administrative burden </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that the EITI should be implemented in a way that limits the administrative burden to both the public and private sector. The Government should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">attend to where the required information is already published or how additional reporting can be integrated into pre-existing mechanisms.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">By giving consideration to non-traditional reporting methods the Government has the opportunity to model innovative new approaches to implementation.  This would demonstrate to countries both compliant and still to join how to adapt and apply EITI in a way that is relevant to each particular environment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Reputational risk to the UK </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Both EITI and the EU Accounting and Transparency Directives aim to increase transparency at the point of extraction, however as a centre for global business the UK must also consider the regulatory framework it provides for London-based and listed companies undertaking extractive work elsewhere. Particular consideration must be given to those companies operating in conflict-affected or weakly governed states.  Recent scandals involving London-listed companies threaten to undermine the UK’s reputation as a stable investment environment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In many cases companies exploit weaknesses in the British regulatory framework, not least our links to the opaque business environments provided by the Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies.  The use of complex corporate structures and nominee directors allows firms to engage with political and military elites in poorly governed states to acquire assets for low prices.  When these are sold on the UK market legitimate companies become implicated in questionable business practices.  Likewise, bribes paid for the rights to extract resources can be laundered through secrecy havens before entering the UK market, posing a serious reputational risk to both investors and the financial sector. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Issues of transparency are compounded by weak stock market regulation. Both the London Stock Exchange (LSE) and its less regulated sub-market the Alternative Investment Market (AIM) have been accused of permitting mining and other extractive companies to list despite poor social, environmental and human rights records. A number companies, such as those highlighted by the London Mining Network, are said to have consistently flouted basic standards of good conduct yet continue to be listed on both LSE and AIM without thorough investigation of alleged misdeeds</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">AIM is of particular concern, having been described as ‘notoriously lax</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’ and ‘like a casino</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’.  Its weaker regulatory framework allows assets of questionable provenance to be traded and attract capital investment on the junior market before being transferred (via acquisition) to the main market</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Thus while more effective regulation of the LSE is welcome, it will not adequately address the potential for UK-listed firms to launder money unless AIM is also reformed</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Again such conditions damage the UK’s reputation as a stable, legitimate market and pose significant risks to investors.  Indeed, investors have been vocal in their support of increased transparency in the extractive industries across global markets for this very reason.  Last month an international consortium of investors wrote to the US Securities and Exchange Commission and National Resources Canada urging global standards for transparency over tax and royalty payments by extractive companies</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  In October 2011 more than twenty investors representing 2.5 trillion Euros in assets publically supported the EU’s then draft legislation on extractive transparency</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Making the UK a centre of excellence for best practice and corporate governance</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A major step towards alleviating this reputational risk would be to combat secrecy havens through the creation of a public register of beneficial company ownership.  At the G8 the Prime Minister committed to creating a UK register and consulting on whether to make it public. We believe that ending the secrecy over beneficial ownership will create a fairer, more transparent and ultimately better governed UK business environment. Putting it in the public domain will improve the quality of the information by allowing many different interested parties to verify data and is in line with the spirit of increase government transparency. Indeed, it is worth noting that the move is recommended by EITI who urge implementing countries to ‘maintain a publicly available register of the beneficial owners of the corporate entities that bid for, operate or invest in extractive assets.’</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The inquiry should also address the loose regulatory framework of the Alternative Investment Market, in particular the lack of due diligence over assets associated with zones of conflict or weak governance.  This should be mandatory on any transactions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">over an agreed size</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. AIM Regulation should be strengthened, specifically by formalising the new requirement ‘to consider the spirit and underlying purpose’ of rules governing the notification of price-sensitive information in the Rules for Nominated Advisers. Detailed recommendations for more effective regulation of AIM have been set out by Rights and Accountability in Development</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When abuses are identified it is vital that strong action is taken against the company in question. There is a serious reputational risk to the UK if the Government permits impunity for companies who partake in illicit activities.  Regulation must be backed by strong enforcement mechanisms. The Serious Fraud Office (SFO) is often unfavourably compared to the US Securities and Exchange Commission for its poorer levels of financing and expertise.  There is particular concern over recent budget cuts to the SFO and their potential impact on its ability to enforce the UK Bribery Act 2010.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">With world-leading anti-bribery legislation that has real potential to prevent UK companies paying bribes in return for extraction rights, it is vital that we have the enforcement mechanisms to hold companies to the standard proscribed.  The Financial Conduct Authority must also contribute to effective enforcement in its capacity as the UK Listing Authority.  We urge the Government to ensure it is equipped with the expertise and resources to effectively hold UK-listed extractive companies to account.    </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> February 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Australia’s Pilot Progress Report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> [pdf].  Available </span><a href="http://eiti.org/files/Australia%20Pilot%20Progress%20Report%20February%202013_0.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">here</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> House of Commons Library, September 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Shale gas and fracking</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> [pdf].  Available </span><a href="https://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=3&amp;ved=0CDwQFjAC&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.parliament.uk%2Fbriefing-papers%2Fsn06073.pdf&amp;ei=6Gg0Uo7NIOig7AadwYDAAw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEhFud3UZQwOgaejL-C96qG9g0DSg&amp;sig2=qEKzbB_zqj1bOq9NYYGhNQ&amp;bvm=bv.52164340,"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">here</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> David Cameron, May 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Letter to Crown Dependency Leaders</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.  Available </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/g8-pm-writes-t